---
import MainLayout from "../../layouts/MainLayout.astro";
import GearIntro from "../../components/GearIntro.astro";
import { getEntry, render } from "astro:content";
import VideoCard from "../../components/VideoCard.astro";

const gear = await getEntry("gear", "knobbler");
if (!gear) throw new Error("Gear not found");
const { Content } = await render(gear);

const videos = [
  {
    id: "PY_IKedjfz8",
    title: "Knobbler for iPad in 60 Seconds",
    description:
      "A quick one-minute overview of Knobbler as an Ableton Live control surface.",
  },
  {
    id: "IXMD_2z16_A",
    title: "Knobbler for iPad — Setup",
    description:
      "Step-by-step setup guide: install the Max for Live device, connect your tablet, and get going.",
  },
  {
    id: "Be4O1vaxjxU",
    title: "Knobbler Feature Walkthrough",
    description:
      "In-depth tour of Knobbler's pages, mapping workflow, navigation, channel strip, and toolbar.",
  },
  {
    id: "m3h8QtVeWb8",
    title: "Knobbler Installation & Feature Walkthrough — 2026",
    description:
      "Updated 15-minute guide covering installation, setup, and all major features of the current release.",
  },
  {
    id: "jklwE2JWsjQ",
    title: "Ableton Live Workflow Magic with Knobbler, Racks, and Variations",
    description:
      "See how Knobbler pairs with Racks and Variations for a powerful, hands-on Ableton Live workflow.",
  },
];
---

<MainLayout title={gear.data.title} description={gear.data.description}>
  <GearIntro
    title={gear.data.title}
    description={gear.data.description}
    url={gear.data.url}
  />

  <div class="section-card video-section">
    <div class="video-section__header">
      <h2>Learn Knobbler</h2>
      <p>
        Official videos from <a
          href="https://www.youtube.com/@zsteinkamp"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">Zack Steinkamp</a
        >, the creator of Knobbler, covering setup and all major features.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="video-grid">
      {
        videos.map((v) => (
          <VideoCard id={v.id} title={v.title} description={v.description} />
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-card knobbler-features-section">
    <h2>Features</h2>
    <p>
      Content and images sourced from <a
        href="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/m4l-Knobbler4/features"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer">plugins.steinkamp.us/m4l-Knobbler4/features</a
      >.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/features-hero.jpg"
        alt="Knobbler in action on an iPad"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>

    <h3 id="knobbler-knobs">Knobbler Knobs</h3>
    <p>
      Knobbler's knobs are very high-resolution (500 steps) and operate at a
      latency that is lower than MIDI. The full multitouch capabilities of your
      device are at your fingertips.
    </p>

    <h4>Knob States</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/knob-states.png"
        alt="Knob state indicator dots"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Knob state indicators</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Knobbler knobs indicate their state with a dot in the upper left corner,
      similar to how it is presented in Ableton Live.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Green Dot</strong> — The parameter is controlled by another device,
        or is mapped to a macro knob. The slider will also be greyed out.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Red Dot</strong> — Automation has been recorded for this parameter.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Grey Dot</strong> — Automation has been overridden for this parameter
        (automation was recorded, but the parameter was changed manually). Tap the
        Re-Enable Automation button in the toolbar to re-enable it.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3 id="knobbler-pages">Knobbler Pages</h3>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-with-none.png"
        alt="Knobbler page with unmapped sliders"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Knobbler page — sliders ready to be mapped</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      This was Knobbler's first feature: a page of sliders that you can map to
      whatever you like. There are two ways to map a Knobbler slider.
    </p>

    <h4>Mapping 1: Selected Param</h4>
    <p>
      Click a parameter on the computer screen, which highlights that parameter
      by highlighting its corners.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/parameter-selected.png"
        alt="A selected parameter highlighted in Ableton Live"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Selected parameter highlighted in Live</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Then tap any unassigned Knobbler slider, and the mapping is done. No modes
      to enter or exit, and the control remains available to be controlled with
      the mouse or modulated by another device in the set.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-knobbler-map.png"
        alt="Tapping an unmapped Knobbler slider to assign it"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Tap any unassigned slider to map it</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h4>Mapping 2: Direct from Bluhand</h4>
    <p>
      On the Bluhand page, tap a parameter name. The parameter's slider will get
      a green outline.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-bluhand-kmap.png"
        alt="Tapping a parameter name on the Bluhand page"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Tap a parameter name on the Bluhand page</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Then go to a Knobbler page. All of the sliders will be highlighted in
      green. Tap any of them (even one that is already mapped) and it will be
      replaced.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-bluhand-kmap-knobbler.png"
        alt="All Knobbler sliders highlighted green for mapping"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>All sliders highlighted — tap one to map</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-bluhand-kmap-after.png"
        alt="Knobbler slider successfully mapped"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Mapping complete</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Knobbler mappings are saved with the Live Set, making recall instant and
      enabling you to work on many songs at once.
    </p>

    <h4>Unmapping</h4>
    <p>
      To unmap a Knobbler slider, tap the Unmap button in the Toolbar. All
      sliders will get a red outline. Tap the slider(s) you wish to unmap, then
      tap the Unmap button again to exit unmapping mode.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-knobbler-unmap.png"
        alt="Knobbler sliders in unmapping mode with red outlines"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Unmapping mode — sliders shown with red outlines</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h4>Default Value</h4>
    <p>
      All sliders in Knobbler respond to a double-tap by resetting the parameter
      to its default value. Double-tap to default.
    </p>

    <h4>Fine Control</h4>
    <p>
      Use two fingers on any slider for 10× precision. This works on all sliders
      throughout the app — Knobbler pages, Bluhand, Channel Strip, Multi-Track
      Mixer, and Current Parameter.
    </p>

    <h4>X-Y Pads</h4>
    <p>
      Two adjacent Knobbler sliders can be linked into an X-Y pad, giving you
      two-dimensional control over a pair of parameters with a single finger.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/link_mode_xy_start.jpg"
        alt="Link button in the toolbar"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Tap the Link button to enter link mode</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/link_mode_xy_link.jpg"
        alt="Tapping between two adjacent sliders to link them"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Tap between two adjacent sliders</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/link_mode_xy_end.jpg"
        alt="Completed X-Y pad"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        X-Y pad created — left slider = X axis, right = Y axis
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      To split an X-Y pad back into two individual sliders, tap the Link button
      in the toolbar, then tap the X-Y pad you want to split. X-Y pad
      assignments are saved per page and persist with your Live Set.
    </p>

    <h4>Select Track</h4>
    <p>
      If you tap the track name under the Knobbler slider, that will select that
      track in Live, which will update the channel strip on the left side of the
      screen. This is a convenient way to access the mixer controls for a
      parameter you have mapped.
    </p>

    <h3 id="bluhand-page">Bluhand Page</h3>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-bluhand-pink.png"
        alt="The Bluhand page showing device parameters"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Bluhand page — parameter-focused device view</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Bluhand gives you a parameter-focused view of the currently selected
      device. Parameter banks are shown above the sliders. In the case of racks,
      Variations controls are shown. The device can be toggled off and on with
      the orange button next to the device title.
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      Make sure you do not turn off the Knobbler device! Otherwise you will have
      to turn it back on using the mouse. :)
    </blockquote>

    <h4>Default Value</h4>
    <p>
      All sliders in Knobbler respond to a double-tap by resetting the parameter
      to its default value. Double-tap to default.
    </p>

    <h4>Variations Support</h4>
    <p>
      When a Rack is selected, the space normally used for Parameter Banks
      changes to show Variations controls.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/variations.png"
        alt="Variations controls for a Rack"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Variations controls replace parameter banks for Racks
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Stored variations are shown with the numbered buttons; the selected
      variation is shown with a brighter button. Tap the Camera icon to store a
      new variation. Tap the Dice icon to randomize the Rack's Macro controls.
    </p>

    <h4>Fast Mapping to Knobbler</h4>
    <p>
      Tap a parameter name on a Bluhand slider to enter Knobbler mapping mode.
      The slider above that parameter name will get a bright green border. Then
      if you visit the Knobbler 1 or Knobbler 2 page, every slider there will
      have the same green border. Tap one of those sliders to map that parameter
      to that Knobbler fader. Fast!
    </p>

    <h3 id="device-shortcuts">Device Shortcuts</h3>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-shortcuts.png"
        alt="Eight shortcut buttons near the top of the screen"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Eight shortcut buttons for instant device access</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Toward the top of the Knobbler and Bluhand pages, there are eight buttons
      that you can use to instantly jump to the most important devices in your
      Live Set.
    </p>

    <h4>Mapping</h4>
    <p>
      With the device you would like to map shown in the Bluhand page, tap an
      unassigned shortcut button. You're done!
    </p>

    <h4>Unmapping</h4>
    <p>
      Tap the Unmap button in the toolbar to enter Unmapping mode. All shortcut
      buttons will be given a red border.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-shortcuts-unmap.png"
        alt="Shortcut buttons in unmapping mode with red outlines"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Tap any button with a red border to unmap it</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Tap any of the buttons to unmap them. Tap the Unmap button again to exit
      Unmapping mode.
    </p>

    <h4>Using the Shortcut Buttons</h4>
    <p>
      Regardless of whether you are on a Bluhand or Knobbler page, tapping a
      shortcut button will take you to the Bluhand page with that device
      selected.
    </p>

    <h3 id="current-parameter">Current Parameter</h3>
    <p>
      The current parameter display shows information about whichever parameter
      is currently selected in Live. When you click a parameter in Ableton, the
      app automatically updates to show the parameter name, device name, track
      name, track color, current value, and the min/max range.
    </p>
    <p>
      The current parameter display is always visible on the Navigation page,
      giving you constant feedback as you work.
    </p>

    <h4>Lock</h4>
    <p>
      You can lock the display to a specific parameter so it stays visible even
      as you click around in Live. Unlock to resume following the selected
      parameter.
    </p>

    <h4>Control</h4>
    <p>
      The current parameter can be adjusted directly from the app via a slider.
      Double-tap to reset to the default value.
    </p>

    <h3 id="external-hardware">External Hardware</h3>
    <p>
      You can use Knobbler with external hardware in conjunction with a device
      like the <code>CC Control</code> device that comes with Live 12. Note that as
      of Live 12.1, <code>CC Control</code> has a defective API implementation and
      does not work properly with Knobbler. Until that device is fixed, you can use
      the free <a
        href="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/m4l-MIDI-CC-Bridge"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer">MIDI CC Bridge</a
      > device instead.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-MIDI-CC-Bridge/images/device-menu.png"
        alt="MIDI CC Bridge Max for Live device"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        MIDI CC Bridge — free workaround for Live 12 CC Control issues
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3 id="navigation">Navigation</h3>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-with-nav.png"
        alt="Navigation panel open on the right side of the screen"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Navigation panel — move through your Live Set at speed
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>Move around your Live Set with more speed and ease than ever before!</p>
    <p>
      Tap a track to open it. Tap a device to select it and show its parameters
      in the Bluhand page. Tracks have a highlight on their left edge, devices
      are highlighted on the right.
    </p>
    <p>
      Group tracks and racks are indicated with a list icon. Tap a Rack to show
      its chains. Tap a chain to see devices inside that chain.
    </p>
    <p>
      Sometimes track colors or names may get out of sync. Tap the Refresh
      button in the Toolbar to fix this.
    </p>

    <h3 id="channel-strip">Channel Strip</h3>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-with-mixer.png"
        alt="Channel strip mixer panel open on the left side"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Channel strip — full mixer control for the selected track
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Take full control over the mixer controls for the currently selected
      track. Tap the button to show the Channel Strip, or swipe it in from the
      left side.
    </p>

    <h4>Sends</h4>
    <p>
      Each send track in your set is represented, including its color. If there
      is not enough space to display all of the sends, you can swipe up and down
      to scroll between them. Slide left and right to increase or decrease the
      amount sent.
    </p>

    <h4>Volume</h4>
    <p>
      This is the mixer volume for the track. Its color will be the same as the
      selected track color.
    </p>

    <h4>Pan</h4>
    <p>Slide left and right to control the pan position.</p>

    <h4>Mute</h4>
    <p>Toggle whether the track is muted.</p>

    <h4>Solo</h4>
    <p>
      Toggles the track's solo state. Respects the user preference around
      exclusive solo.
    </p>

    <h4>Record Arm</h4>
    <p>
      Tap to toggle this track's record arm state. Respects the user preference
      around exclusive arm.
    </p>

    <h4>Toggle Record Enable</h4>
    <p>
      A long press on the Record Arm button will disable input entirely. This is
      useful if you are in Arrangement view and you want to record automation
      over existing MIDI clips without changing the clips. Otherwise, the MIDI
      clips are all merged into a single clip. Tap the record arm button again
      to re-enable inputs and arm the track for recording.
    </p>

    <h4>Crossfader Controls</h4>
    <p>
      On tracks and return tracks, an <kbd>A</kbd> or <kbd>B</kbd> button are shown,
      which allows you to assign that track to one side of the crossfader or another.
      If you select the Main track, the <kbd>A</kbd>/<kbd>B</kbd> buttons are replaced
      with a crossfader slider.
    </p>

    <h4>Default Value</h4>
    <p>
      All sliders in Knobbler respond to a double-tap by resetting the parameter
      to its default value. Double-tap to default.
    </p>

    <h3 id="session-view-clips">Session View Clips</h3>
    <p>
      A full session view clip grid right on your device. Launch, record,
      rename, and color clips and scenes without touching your mouse. Real-time
      playback state, group track folding, scene management, and more.
    </p>

    <h3 id="multi-track-mixer">Multi-Track Mixer</h3>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/mixer-ipad.png"
        alt="Full-screen multi-track mixer"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Multi-Track Mixer — horizontally scrollable full-screen view
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The multi-track mixer provides a full-screen, horizontally scrollable view
      of all tracks in your Live Set. It gives you hands-on control of volume,
      pan, mute, solo, record arm, sends, and crossfader assignments across
      multiple tracks at once. Only the tracks visible on screen are actively
      monitored, so it stays responsive even with large sets.
    </p>

    <h4>Volume and Pan</h4>
    <p>
      Each strip has a volume fader and pan control. Double-tap to reset either
      to its default value. Volume automation state is shown with a colored
      indicator, matching the same automation dot colors used on Knobbler knobs
      (green for controlled, red for recorded automation, grey for overridden).
      Tap the volume value to open a dedicated pan and send control window.
    </p>

    <h4>Mute, Solo, and Record Arm</h4>
    <p>
      Toggle mute, solo, and record arm per strip. Record arm respects the
      exclusive arm preference. Disabling input is also supported for recording
      automation over existing MIDI clips.
    </p>

    <h4>Sends</h4>
    <p>
      Send levels for up to 12 return tracks are available per strip. Send
      colors match their corresponding return track colors.
    </p>

    <h4>Crossfader</h4>
    <p>Assign tracks to crossfader side A or B directly from the mixer.</p>

    <h4>Meters</h4>
    <p>
      Output level meters are shown for all visible strips, displaying left
      channel, right channel, and combined output levels in real time. Toggle
      their display with the Meters button in the toolbar.
    </p>

    <h3 id="toolbar">Toolbar</h3>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar.png"
        alt="Knobbler toolbar"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Knobbler's toolbar, echoing Ableton Live's with additional controls
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Knobbler's toolbar echoes a lot of the items in Ableton Live's toolbar,
      with some Knobbler-specific additions.
    </p>

    <h4>Show / Hide Channel Strip Mixer</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-mixer.png"
        alt="Channel strip toggle button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>
      Toggle the appearance of the channel strip on the left edge of the screen.
      You can also swipe sideways from the edge to show and hide it.
    </p>

    <h4>Refresh Display</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-refresh.png"
        alt="Refresh button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>Requests an update of all data from the computer.</p>

    <h4>Unmapping Mode</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-unmap.png"
        alt="Unmapping mode button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>
      This button toggles Unmapping mode on and off. When Unmapping mode is
      engaged, Knobbler sliders and Shortcut buttons have a red border. Tap the
      slider or button to unmap it.
    </p>

    <h4>Tempo Section</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-tempo.png"
        alt="Tempo section of the toolbar"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>Tap tempo, tempo display and editing, and metronome control.</p>

    <h4>Transport Controls</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-transport.png"
        alt="Transport controls — play, stop, record"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>
      Play, stop, and record. Pressing <kbd>Stop</kbd> a second time will send the
      playhead to the beginning of the song. Pressing a third time will silence anything
      that is playing. The record button respects the "Start Transport With Record"
      preference.
    </p>

    <h4>Overdub MIDI</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-overdub-midi.png"
        alt="Overdub MIDI button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>
      When enabled, recorded MIDI data is merged with existing MIDI clips. When
      disabled, recorded MIDI data will replace existing clips.
    </p>

    <h4>Re-Enable Automation</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-reenable.png"
        alt="Re-Enable Automation button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>
      If automation is recorded for a parameter, but that parameter is manually
      adjusted, the automation will be disabled and shown in grey. Click this
      button to re-enable the automation everywhere that it is disabled.
    </p>

    <h4>Capture MIDI</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-capture-midi.png"
        alt="Capture MIDI button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>
      Click this button to capture all MIDI data recorded since changing tracks.
      This is a great way to be noodling into some inspiration and not have to
      stop and record — which usually loses some of that zesty mojo.
    </p>

    <h4>Session Automation Overdub</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-session-automation-overdub.png"
        alt="Session Automation Overdub button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>
      When enabled, any automation moves made while session clips are playing
      are recorded into the clip. This is an awesome way to build layers of
      evolution into your sounds.
    </p>

    <h4>Loop</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-loop.png"
        alt="Loop toggle button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>Toggle whether the Arrangement view transport loop is enabled.</p>

    <h4>Previous / Next Locator</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-locators.png"
        alt="Previous and Next Locator buttons"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>
      These buttons allow you to navigate to locators in your Live Set. The
      beginning of the song and the loop ending point are default locators.
    </p>

    <h4>Show / Hide Navigation</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/ipad-toolbar-nav.png"
        alt="Toggle Navigation button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
    </figure>
    <p>
      Toggles the display of the Navigation widget on the right side of the
      screen. You can also swipe in from the side to show it, and swipe from its
      left edge to hide it.
    </p>

    <h3 id="setup-page">Setup Page</h3>
    <p>The Setup page has three sections: Connection, Settings, and Debug.</p>

    <h4>Connection</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/setup-discovery.png"
        alt="Setup page showing device discovery"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Knobbler advertises itself on your local network for auto-discovery
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Knobbler advertises itself on your local network. Under "Found These
      Knobblers", tap the entry for your computer and the Host, Device Port, and
      App Port fields will be filled in automatically. Tap <kbd>Refresh</kbd> to rescan
      the network. You can also enter the host or IP and port numbers manually if
      you prefer.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/setup-connected.png"
        alt="Setup page showing a successful connection"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Green banner confirms a successful connection</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Once connected, you'll see a green "Connection Successful!" banner with
      the device version number. Tap <kbd>Test</kbd> to verify the connection, or
      <kbd>Clear</kbd> to reset the fields and start over.
    </p>

    <h4>Settings</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/setup-settings.png"
        alt="Setup settings tab"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Settings tab with display and behavior options</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Track Overview</strong> — show the colored track overview bar in the
        mixer
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Crossfader (A/B)</strong> — show crossfader assignment buttons on
        mixer strips
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Auto-Collapse Chains</strong> — automatically collapse rack chains
        when navigating away
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Level Meters</strong> — show real-time level meters on mixer strips
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Haptic Feedback</strong> — enable haptic feedback on supported devices
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Debug</h4>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/cache/m4l-Knobbler4/docs/images/setup-debug.png"
        alt="Setup debug tab"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Debug tab with OSC log for troubleshooting</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The Debug tab shows app version info, build number, server details, and
      subscription status. The OSC Log displays incoming and outgoing messages
      in real time — useful for troubleshooting connection issues.
    </p>

    <h4>Version Checks</h4>
    <p>
      If the Knobbler device that the app is communicating with is too old, a
      warning message will be shown. This message also includes a link to
      download the latest Knobbler device.
    </p>

    <h3 id="multi-device-support">Multi-Device Support</h3>
    <p>
      You can use multiple phones and tablets simultaneously with multiple
      Knobbler instances. Add as many instances of the Knobbler device as you
      have devices, and ensure each instance has a unique "Device Port" setting.
      Each device operates independently — use one for faders, another for the
      mixer, a phone for clips, or whatever combination suits your workflow.
    </p>

    <p class="manual-source">
      Content sourced from <a
        href="https://plugins.steinkamp.us/m4l-Knobbler4/features"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer">plugins.steinkamp.us/m4l-Knobbler4/features</a
      > by <a
        href="https://steinkamp.us/"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer">Zack Steinkamp</a
      >.
    </p>
  </div>
</MainLayout>

